ANTHRAX, HUMAN, LIVESTOCK - RUSSIA: (ASTRAKHAN)
***********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

[1]
Date: Sat 20 Sep 2008
Source: Broadcasting station Echo of Moscow [in Russian, trans. Mod.NP, edited]
<http://echo.msk.ru/news/541788-echo.html>


Three local residents contracted anthrax in the Astrakhan region. The
patients with symptoms of the cutaneous form of this dangerous
disease are now in hospital in the Volgograd region. [which borders
the Astrakhan region. - Mod.NP]

The source of the infection was meat from slaughtered cattle.

The Commission of the Ministry of Health in the Astrakhan region went
to the district where patients were reported in order to investigate
the source of infection and look for other possible cases.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Historic animal burial sites exist in their hundreds in Russia, most
locations are unknown, and are the main cause for ongoing livestock
anthrax. Before the latter part of last century [20th] anthrax
carcasses were not burnt but only buried. - Mod.NP]

******
[2]
Date: Mon 22 Sep 2008
Source: MVKursk.ru [in Russian, trans. Mod.NR, edited]
<http://www.mvkursk.ru/all_news/9211.html>


Anthrax cases in Astrakhan
--------------------------
At the end of the last week [week of 15 Sep 2008], 3 people from
Ushakovka village in the Chernoyar district, Astrakhan, were
hospitalized with the cutaneous form of anthrax.

According to preliminary information from the Ministry of Emergency
Situations, the disease occurred as a result of slaughter of [sick]
livestock. Two more people from the same village were hospitalized on
Saturday [20 Sep 2008], but they do not have symptoms of anthrax yet.
32 contact people have been identified and they are under medical
observation. Anti-epidemic prevention measures are currently in place.

--
Communicated by:
HealthMap Alerts via ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Our thanks to Mod.NP & Mod NR from ProMED-RUS for their translations.

Astrakhan on the north shore of the Caspian Sea with Volgograd on its
northern border can be located on the map at
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/commonwealth/russiaaddivisions.jpg>
For Astrakhan, see
<http://encarta.msn.com/encnet/features/mapcenter/map.aspx?TextLatitude=39.45&TextLongitude=-98.907&TextAltitude=0&TextSelectedEntity=39070&MapStyle=Comprehensive&MapSize=Large&MapStyleSelectedIndex=0&searchTextMap=astrakhan%2C+russia&MapStylesList=Comprehensive&ZoomOnMapClickCheck=on>,
zoom in on the northern border of this oblast and you will find
Ushakovka in the NW corner, close to the Volga river. Which explains
why the patients were hospitalised in Volgograd. - Mod.MHJ]
